  131  Comment by stsamster — July 20, 2011 @ 3:24 pm

    I think that maybe it would help to think instead of each transition from point to point, e.g. P1 to P2 to P3 to think of transitions between pairs of points, e.g. (P1,P2) to (P2,P3) to (P3,P4) where the first coordinate is the old point and the second coordinate is the new point. Note: (P1,P2) is a different point-pair from (P2,P1) in this definition. In such a case, each transition from one point-pair to the next is unique since the orientation of the line is specified and the line rotates in one direction. One can then compose a graph where the nodes are point-pairs and the edges are transitions. By this construction each node has exactly one outgoing edge. Since transitions always occur and the graph is finite, a cycle will ultimately emerge via the transitions. The question then reduces to whether or not one can have one point-pair that is reached by two different point-pairs. e.g. Can we geometrically have transitions P1 to P2 to P3 and P4 to P2 to P3 while none of the points are colinear?
     
